  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These laws and frameworks are designed to promote global cooperation in the fight against financial crimes. Key international laws and initiatives include:\n\n### 1. **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**\n   - The FATF is an intergovernmental organization established in 1989 to combat money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.\n   - The FATF sets international standards known as the *FATF Recommendations*, which provide a comprehensive framework for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures.\n   - Member countries and jurisdictions are expected to implement these recommendations into their national laws and regulations.\n\n### 2. **United Nations Conventions**\n   - **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** (Vienna Convention): This was one of the first international treaties to address money laundering, particularly in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** (Palermo Convention): This convention requires member states to criminalize money laundering and establish measures to prevent it.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)** (Merida Convention): This convention includes provisions to combat money laundering related to corruption and the illicit enrichment of public officials.\n\n### 3. **European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives**\n   - The EU has issued several AML Directives (e.g., the 4th, 5th, and 6th AMLD) to harmonize AML regulations across member states. These directives require EU countries to establish AML frameworks, including customer due diligence, reporting suspicious transactions, and maintaining beneficial ownership registers.\n\n### 4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**\n   - While not a law, the Basel Committee has issued principles and guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering, such as the *Core Principles for Effective Banking Supervision*.\n\n### 5. **Other Regional and Multilateral Initiatives**\n   - Various regional organizations, such as the Asia/Pacific Group on Money Laundering (APG), the Caribbean Financial Action Task Force (CFATF), and the Eurasian Group on Combating Money Laundering and Financing of Terrorism (EAG), work to implement AML standards within their regions.\n\n### Key Principles of International AML Laws:\n   - Criminalization of money laundering.\n   - Establishment of financial intelligence units (FIUs) to collect and analyze suspicious transaction reports.\n   - Implementation of customer due diligence (CDD) and know-your-customer (KYC) requirements.\n   - Enforcement of cross-border cooperation and information sharing among countries.\n   - Freezing, seizure, and confiscation of illicit proceeds.\n\n### Enforcement:\n   - Countries are expected to transpose international AML standards into their national laws and enforce them through regulatory bodies, law enforcement agencies, and financial institutions.\n   - Non-compliance with international AML standards can result in sanctions, inclusion on watchlists (e.g., FATF's \"grey list\" or \"black list\"), and restricted access to global financial systems.\n\nIn summary, while there is no single global law against money laundering, a network of international treaties, standards, and initiatives provides a coordinated approach to combating this crime worldwide.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
